<TITLE>Biz Buzz, Jan. 29, 2017</TITLE>
<TEXT>By Staff 
Saturday, January 28, 2017 
 
The  Salvation Army Thrift Store formerly located at 1155 N. Fourth St. has moved into the old Harbert Lumber building at 240 North Ave. and is open for business. 
 
Customers can make purchases using cash or check while the internet is being installed, said Capt. Steve Staneart , commanding officer of the Grand Junction corps. 
 
Staneart said an arrangement with the Harbert family allowed the move, which may be permanent. 
 
The Harbert family has been on our board for generations, and they were very kind to us to allow us to go in there for something we could afford, he said. 
 
The Salvation Army is leasing the space for a year, with an option to buy the building if its a good fit. 
 
Staneart said the building has nearly double the space as the old thrift store, and includes a yard that will be useful since the organization just received a license to do after-school care for children. 
 
The organization will keep the former store building and plans on repurposing it for after-school programs offering arts, education, character development and sports. 
 
The Salvation Army also spruced up its Clifton store at 3227 I-70 Business Loop B, Staneart said. 
 
The stores are open from 8 a.m. to 6 p.m., Monday through Saturday. 
 
For more information, call 242-7513 or visit grandjunction.salvationarmy.org. 
 
 Customers of the building materials supply company ProBuild , 2773 Riverside Parkway, probably have noticed the new signage and new name of the operation, Builders FirstSource , as they whizzed by along the parkway. 
 
Its not a new business  just the final step in an acquisition process that began in July 2015. 
 
Were just now getting the signs changed, an employee at the newly branded store said this week, adding that the store is the same as what people remember. 
 
At the time it was announced that Builders FirstSource was acquiring ProBuild, officials said the combined company would help better focus on their four critical customer segments: production builders, custom builders, multifamily/commercial builders, and repair and remodel businesses. The leverage of being a part of a national network  Builders FirstSource had 430 locations, and served 74 of the top 100 metropolitan statistical areas across 40 states at the time of the deal  is presumably a perk of the combination. 
 
